otes: 127 | Comments: 9 | Created: 2026-05-06           │\n3: │ https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction/discus │\n4: │ sion/697418                                                                  │\n5: ╰──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯\n7: 🌆\n8: inbox%2F4080021%2F3f56527c733365a94d929bdc0600c7ef%2Fig_023b4ba06ac0441e0169fa92\n9: 48ca54819aacb93888a02601a8.png?generation=1778029361497538&alt=media\n11: ── 9 Comments ──\n13: eugene ▲1 2026-05-06\n14: Thank you for this diagram! But what about typewells? Dow you know how does it\n15: work ? Why is TVT a straight line in typewell data? Isn't TVT the thickness of\n16: the Layers? And if we drill vertically, then we pass through several layers and\n17: the TVT should change from layer to layer right? Or is vertical only for\n18: TargetLayer? 😵‍💫\n20: Manish Swami ▲2 2026-05-07\n21: Typewell.csv  act as ground truth of horizontal_well.csv\n23: Navneet ▲1 2026-05-07\n24: Informative Diagram of the Problem @zacchaeus\n26: RMorrison ▲8 2026-05-07\n27: This diagram makes a lot of sense to me, but I'm still confused on the magnitude\n28: of TVT in the data. Each TVT value is larger than both Z or the top depths of\n29: the individual layers at a given MD. I'm assuming all units are in feet. This\n30: diagram doesn't work if TVT > Z, so I suspect ROGII is using a different\n31: convention here. I think TVT is loosely defined and used differently by\n32: different parties. A clarification about the definition here by ROGII with a\n33: diagram would certainly be appreciated.\n35: Ra'uf Fauzan Rambe ▲1 2026-05-28\n36: This diagram is already good to be used as an education in this Geology\n37: Prediction\n39: 2026-06-08\n41: ▲1 2026-06-08\n43: ▲1 2026-06-08\n45: Stitch Clarity 2026-06-09\n46: Hi everyone. I’m new here, and before I start commenting more seriously in this\n47: competition, I wanted to say this once clearly and respectfully.\n49: I noticed the line under the comment box: “Be patient, be friendly, and focus on\n50: ideas. We’re all here to learn and improve.” I LOVE THAT!, because that is\n51: honestly the only reason I want to participate here.\n53: I’m not here to argue, flex, advertise, or act like I know more than anyone. I’m\n54: trying to learn the problem, share useful perspectives, and ask better\n55: questions. I come from a very structured way of thinking. Over time I’ve tried\n56: to break my own reasoning process into layers: problem, signal, pattern,\n57: constraint, contradiction, missing context, and so on. I call that kind of work\n58: Stitch Clarity in my own system, but the simple version is this: I try to take\n59: messy information and organize it into something people can actually reason\n60: through.\n62: Because of that, my comments can sometimes look very structured. I know that can\n63: read strangely online. I’ve had that happen in other communities, where people\n64: assumed I was being automated or trying to game attention, when really I was\n65: just trying to be careful and helpful. So I want to be transparent up front: I’m\n66: a real person, I’m reading, I’m thinking, and I’m trying to contribute in good\n67: faith.\n69: This diagram helped me a lot, and I’ve found myself coming back to it because it\n70: exposes the part of the problem I keep thinking about: maybe TVT here is not\n71: just “depth” in the simple visual sense. Maybe it behaves more like a local\n72: geology-position coordinate, where the hard part is understanding the transform\n73: between MD, Z, GR, TVT_input, the typewell, and the hidden prediction zone.\n75: The questions I keep circling are:\n77: 1 Is there a per-well or per-group offset/scale between TVT, Z, MD, and the\n78: layer surfaces?\n79: 2 Is TVT mainly constrained by continuity from TVT_input, or can the\n80: stratigraphic frame shift after prediction start?\n81: 3 Should the horizontal GR curve be aligned or warped against the typewell GR\n82: curve instead of compared directly?\n83: 4 Could repeated constants across wells suggest grouped geological transforms?\n84: 5 Are some errors really geology errors, or are they hidden\n85: coordinate/alignment errors?\n86: 6 Is the typewell best treated as a reference signature rather than a direct\n87: vertical lookup?\n89: I’m not stating any of that as fact. I’m just trying to frame the problem in a\n90: way that might reveal useful mathematical structure.\n92: So before I spend a lot of time posting ideas here, I wanted to ask plainly: is\n93: this kind of contribution welcome? If I’m off base, I’m happy to be corrected.\n94: If this is useful, I’d like to keep learning and sharing ideas in that spirit.\n96: Either way, I appreciate the diagram. It gave me a better starting point.\n\n### rogii_discussion_698825.md\n1: ╭─ How Geologists Interpret Wells: Some Helpful Tips ──────────────────────────╮\n2: │ Author: Igor Kuvaev | Votes: 51 | Comments: 3 | Created: 2026-05-11          │\n3: │ https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction/discus │\n4: │ sion/698825                                                                  │\n5: ╰──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯\n7: Kagglers, you are doing great so far, and we are excited to see the improving\n8: RMSE on the leaderboard. In the comments on this post, I will share some helpful\n9: tricks that geologists use to come up with the best interpretations.\n11: ── 3 Comments ──\n13: Igor Kuvaev ▲3 2026-05-11\n14: GR from the lateral before the Prediction Start point has better resolution than\n15: the GR from the type well.\n17: If the well is going in the negative direction in the TVT domain from the\n18: Prediction Start point, then the correlation with the GR from the lateral will\n19: be better. Therefore, it is better to use the GR from the lateral before the\n20: Prediction Start point for the lateral GR correlation.\n22: In my image, the red curve correlates better with the green curve than the type\n23: well (gray).\n25: 🌆\n26: inbox%2F31464355%2F33faa3899bb47175c4a0b2edb5eb3661%2FGR_before_PS.png?generatio\n27: n=1778525111769053&alt=media\n29: Igor Kuvaev ▲5 2026-05-11\n30: Lateral Well GR correlates on itself. Lateral Well GR has better resolution than\n31: Typewell GR\n33: 🌆\n34: inbox%2F31464355%2Ff59c00700a6b51b1fc2ab4022683a215%2FGR_correlates%20on%20itsel\n35: f.png?generation=1778527935587790&alt=media\n37: 🌆\n38: inbox%2F31464355%2F6b596aa59019f6963745c2d1a90c18c4%2FGR_correlates%20on%20itsel\n39: f%202.png?generation=1778527957181745&alt=media\n41: Igor Kuvaev ▲5 2026-05-11\n42: Formation Dip (angle of the formation) from the nearby wells should be similar\n44: 🌆\n45: inbox%2F31464355%2Fb97c90e99c362fd73a782c25dbffeae1%2FOffset%20dip.png?generatio\n46: n=1778528201656306&alt=media\n\n### rogii_discussion_699853.md\n1: ╭─ multi-trajectory prediction (MTP) with deep CNN for welllog inversion ──────╮\n2: │ Author: hengck23 | Votes: 47 | Comments: 92 | Created: 2026-05-15            │\n3: │ https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction/discus │\n4: │ sion/699853                                                                  │\n5: ╰──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯\n7: example notebook\n8: https://www.kaggle.com/code/hengck23/cnn-mtp-example?scriptVersionId=320093395\n10: arvix paper: \"Direct Multi-Modal Inversion of Geophysical Logs Using Deep\n11: Learning\" - Sergey Alyaev\n12: https://arxiv.org/pdf/2201.01871\n13: https://nfes.org/assets/workshop2022/ambrus_sequential_multi_mode_inversion_post\n14: er.pdf\n17: [2D Heatmap Input] ──> [Regression Head (CNN)] ──> [MDN Predictor (MLP)] ──>\n18: [Multi-Trajectory Output]\n20: example of heatmap is shown below.\n21: The Mixture Density Network (MDN) Predictor : for multiple paths hypothesis\n22: (like k-beam).\n24: if you can identify match keypoints in GR signals, then you 