found a paper on drop-DTW\n141: (dropping invalid segments), it didn't work well because of noise. maybe i\n142: should learn the dropping and wraping i instead (of using DP)\n144: 🌆\n145: inbox%2F113660%2Ffc738ccfc225df547faa141545164e56%2FSelection_3665.png?generatio\n146: n=1779091598108732&alt=media\n148: 🌆\n149: inbox%2F113660%2F6764f6c760325974da37aeef6fc5ccaf%2FSelection_3666.png?generatio\n150: n=1779091874834092&alt=media\n152: ROGII used another kind of feature image\n154: hengck23 ▲2 2026-05-18\n155: 🌆\n156: inbox%2F113660%2F6b3c30814618336c2f27b192da981e59%2FSelection_3667.png?generatio\n157: n=1779093686204434&alt=media\n159: cnn should be very good to capture these micro box patterns (pairs of 2d\n160: signal). these are just like 2d tokens. But i need to recreate ROGII segment\n161: endpoints annotations.\n163: 🌆\n164: inbox%2F113660%2Fe2b9ca5e21d0b0824f07e6bf5f7fb51e%2FSelection_3669.png?generatio\n165: n=1779094329932256&alt=media\n167: Tom ▲1 2026-05-18\n168: Thanks, this is very useful info\n170: hengck23 ▲4 2026-05-20\n171: what you get if you use unet and do \"blood vessel\" segmentation\n173: 🌆\n174: inbox%2F113660%2F1644b9d462a6dc335c4524519b9f0fc4%2FSelection_3697.png?generatio\n175: n=1779280718291901&alt=media validtation\n177: 🌆\n178: inbox%2F113660%2Fa1374e43674b9a496d943f24c69b25f6%2FSelection_3696.png?generatio\n179: n=1779280730592253&alt=media 🌆\n180: inbox%2F113660%2Ff2f50ae71956df1388063a8347bf0ae8%2FSelection_3693.png?generatio\n\n### rogii_discussion_700424.md\n1: ╭─ Share an UI visualizer  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮\n2: │ Author: Tom | Votes: 47 | Comments: 61 | Created: 2026-05-17                 │\n3: │ https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction/discus │\n4: │ sion/700424                                                                  │\n5: ╰──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯\n7: 🌆\n8: inbox%2F4310004%2F8fe8f43532b152aa5a7637b7d6f1a2fe%2FUI1.png?generation=17790220\n9: 20724846&alt=media\n11: Feel free to use it: https://github.com/tom99763/rogii-viewer\n13: And some EDA & directions in attachments. I suggest people to read glossary.html\n14: first to clarify some confused definition.\n16: I really like this explaination about TVT:\n19: Analogy: TVT is the “floor number” in a geological building\n21: Imagine the geology as a completed high-rise building, where each floor\n22: represents a different rock layer (ANCC, Austin Chalk, Eagle Ford, Buda, etc.)\n24: Typewell = the elevator shaft: it goes vertically from the top floor to the\n25: basement, recording “the GR at this layer is X” as it passes through each floo\n26: Horizontal well = a person walking inside the building:  moving along the\n27: hallway of a certain floor, sometimes going up or down between floors.\n28: TVT = which floor is this person currently on?\n31: Update GR Mismatch Visualizer\n33: 🌆\n34: inbox%2F4310004%2F5b91ffbfc5d669a76d10fe1cb409dcb5%2FGR.png?generation=177903061\n35: 1267623&alt=media\n37: ── 61 Comments ──\n39: Tom ▲3 2026-05-17\n40: This plot seems showing a hidden insight\n42: 🌆\n43: inbox%2F4310004%2Fd0df1bc4db7dfa9a0ac8a8689037f967%2Finsights.png?generation=177\n44: 9025047785552&alt=media\n46: hengck23 ▲3 2026-05-17\n47: U can add following to cnn feature:\n49: 1 Self correlation, good for identifying moving reverse\n50: 2 Neighbouring well correlation\n52: hengck23 ▲4 2026-05-17\n53: Normal dtw assume monotonic seq and cannot match reverse index, so be careful if\n54: you use it.\n56: 2026-05-17\n58: Gaurav Rawat ▲2 2026-05-18\n59: love the eda via claude here very nice to understand the comp ..\n61: Tom ▲3 2026-05-18\n62: This comp is really complicated. There are many details haven't been coveraged\n64: hengck23 ▲3 2026-05-18\n65: one of the few competitions left that humans must do the problem definition\n66: first before applying agent optimization\n68: Tom ▲1 2026-05-18\n69: Turning \"plan mode\" in Claude and carefully define the problem by myself worked\n70: well for me.\n72: Tom ▲3 2026-05-18\n73: Workflow (every new experiment):\n75: 1 Restate the geological problem (physical reality + constraints + signals)\n76: 2 Abstract it into a mathematical problem (alignment? inpainting? inverse\n77: problem? assignment? consensus?)\n78: 3 Map each domain concept to a model component\n79: 4 Explore multiple reasonable formulations in parallel\n80: 5 Only implement after the formulation is finalized\n82: Navneet ▲-1 2026-05-18\n83: Cool UI visualizer @tom99763\n85: Tom ▲4 2026-05-18\n86: I made a NN-based approach with some probabilistic modeling similar to\n87: @jeroencottaar Yale/UNC-CH solution. I haven't submitted yet but it seems a good\n88: direction.\n90: 🌆\n91: inbox%2F4310004%2F501a4be8bddc4492da4fd2bfac3fbd52%2Fensemble_vs_truth_5wells_v2\n92: .png?generation=1779095472915796&alt=media\n94: 🌆\n95: inbox%2F4310004%2F44863581fda421aee8b3c431f68898ae%2Fheatmap_boxes_5wells.png?ge\n96: neration=1779096241756462&alt=media\n98: hengck23 ▲2 2026-05-18\n99: maybe this is useful for you: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fEf6i2A0jdo\n100: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vQDbKR3NAlM\n102: check the lecture from 00 to 05 etc\n104: PatrickAIForFun ▲2 2026-05-18\n105: When you say similar to Jeroen's solution, do you mean you actually modelled a\n106: prior and are optimizing the TVT math to minimize some measruement of mismatch\n107: between the TVTs? If yes, this is highly interesting, but I don't see how a CNN\n108: would fit into this. What am I missing or are you willing to share more?\n110: Tom ▲3 2026-05-18\n111: Yes, I’ve actually built few priors and have been working on minimizing several\n112: measurements. I’ll release it once I have more completed experiments and the\n113: full map is built.\n115: hengck23 ▲2 2026-05-18\n116: \", but I don't see how a CNN would fit into this\" . put your prior in the loss:\n118: loss = regression loss + classification loss  + \"too different from the prior\n119: loss\"\n121: if you use probability:\n122: too different from the prior loss = P( solution not drawn from prior\n123: disturibution)\n125: if you assume Gaussian, then it is related to \"distance from prior solution\"\n127: ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n128: similarly, if you use physics or geology equations (as prior), then it is loss =\n129: regression loss + classification loss  + \"much much the solution follows physics\n130: equations\"\n132: ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n133: if there is prior or physics, maybe predict residual is easier: solution =\n134: residual + prior\n136: Tom 2026-05-18\n137: I use this package: https://docs.pyro.ai/en/stable/\n139: hengck23 ▲2 2026-05-18\n140: i have a suggestion for you. use seq transformer to learn segments (span of md\n141: of similar dip) and output as:\n144: segmentation output:\n145: 1111222222333333333333334444444444444444455666666666666666\n147: auxilarly ouput\n148: dip\n149: xxxyyyzzzz\n151: DTW\n152: etc ....\n154: tvt\n157: actually segmenting should be the first step\n159: you can measure the goodness of each segment by GR fitting or DTW, so it is a\n160: \"physics model\"\n162: ask chatgpt to make segmentation ground truth by considering gradients (-1,0,+1)\n163: of tvt and link them up (or a very slow method called monotonic regression on\n164: gradient)\n166: ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n167: note, the segmntation results is not unqiue. so we can have top-k segmentation\n168: prediction\n170: Mohit ▲-1 2026-05-18\n171: Great work out there also how is nn aproach used here?\n173: Gaurav Rawat 2026-05-18\n174: I try to do nowadays grill me for it to also grill before advising ..\n176: Durga Kumari ▲-1 2026-05-18\n177: This is incredibly helpful, especially the TVT analogy.\n179: hengck23 ▲3 2026-05-18\n180: https://youtu.be/VgzFt7xknGo?si=rwz9Kv2oi3ZwniBE\n\n### rogii_discussion_701767.md\n1: Discussion 701767 not found in database.\n\n### rogii_discussion_701881.md\n1: Discussion 701881 not found in database.\n\n### rogii_discussion_702131.md\n1: ╭─ A geophysicist's take: domain priors + Q-3D tortuosity (public notebook + r─╮\n2: │ Author: Matteo Niccoli | Votes: 16 | Comments: 0 | Created: 2026-05-21       │\n3: │ https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction/discus │\n4: │ sion/702131                                                                  │\n5: ╰──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯\n7: ┏━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━┓\n8: ┃                  Kaggle discussion post - ROGII competition                  ┃\n9: ┗━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━┛\n11: ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n12: Sharing a notebook and a public repo that approach this competition from a\n13: geological reasoning angle rather than pure ML optimization.\n15: Notebook:\n16: https://www.kaggle.com/code/mycarta/rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction-toolkit\n18: GitHub repo:  https://github.com/mycarta/rogii-geosteering-toolkit\n20: Single LightGBM, no particle filters or stacking. Mid-pack on the leaderboard,\n21: but the findings may be useful to others working on this problem:\n23: • Within-well TVT-Z decoupling. The global TVT-vs-Z correlation is r = -0.96,\n24: but within a single lateral it's essentially zero (mean slope +0.057). The\n25: global signal is cross-well structural elevation dominated by build-section\n26: geometry. Features based on the global relationship don't work until you\n27: account for this.\n28: • Q-3D tortuosity (Jing et al. 2022) was the most useful domain feature in the\n29: ablation (-0.107 RMSE). High tortuosity = active steering = formation\n30: deviating from plan.\n31: • Signed drilling azimuth matters. Opposite directions along the same line see\n32: the formation in opposite sequence. The updip/downdip distinction is real and\n33: the model uses it via sin/cos azimuth encoding paired with dZ/dMD.\n34: • Well-level AEON features (Catch22 + ClaSP) made the model worse (+0.476\n35: RMSE). Well-level features under GroupKFold overfit on cross-well noise.\n36: Documented as a negative result in the ablation table.\n37: • Considered Verde's BlockKFold for spatial CV, rejected it. Validation wells\n38: are spatially interleaved with training (interpolation, not extrapolation),\n39: so spatial blocking is more pessimistic than the actual test condition. Used\n40: StratifiedGroupKFold stratified by signed azimuth, median TVT, and spatial\n41: location instead.\n43: The notebook includes a cumulative ablation table, Phase 1 spatial recon figures\n44: (well center map, azimuth rose, lateral slope distribution), a\n45: MASS-equivalent-to-NCC pedagogical demo, and a Q-3D tortuosity visualization.\n47: The GitHub repo has the reusable toolkit modules (wellbore tortuosity from XYZ\n48: trajectories, log despiking, sliding distance correlation) and two methodology\n49: write-ups on the TVT-Z decoupling finding and the AEON evaluation.\n51: Feedback welcome, especially from anyone with geosteering or horizontal drilling\n52: experience. What domain features would you add?\n54: No comments.\n\n### rogii_discussion_702919.md\n1: ╭─ Dynamic Programming for TVT Tracking: What Worked, What Didn't, and What th─╮\n2: │ Author: Matteo Niccoli | Votes: 5 | Comments: 0 | Created: 2026-05-27        │\n3: │ https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/rogii-wellbore-geology-prediction/discus │\n4: │ sion/702919                                                                  │\n5: ╰──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯\n8: ┏━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━┓\n9: ┃                                                                              ┃\n10: ┗━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━┛\n12: Dynamic Programming for TVT Tracking: What Worked, What Didn't, and What the Gap\n13: Tells Us\n15: ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n16: Following up on my earlier discussion on domain priors, I tried a different\n17: approach to TVT tracking: dynamic programming (DP).\n19: The idea in plain terms: The bit traces a physical path through the formation.\n20: TVT at one position constrains what TVT can be at the next position; it can't\n21: jump 50 ft in one sample. Most trackers in this competition (particle filters,\n22: beam search) use heuristics to exploit this constraint. DP is the brute-force\n23: alternative: evaluate every possible TVT path through the typewell state space\n24: and pick the one that best matches the observed GR log, subject to a smoothness\n25: penalty. No randomness, no pruning, guaranteed global optimum for each parameter\n26: set. The trade-off is that you discretize the state space (~400 candidate TVT\n27: positions in a +/-200 ft window around the anchor).\n29: I ran five configurations with different smoothness settings, from \"stiff\"\n30: (strongly resist TVT changes between positions, producing smooth paths that\n31: capture the broad trend) to \"loose\" (allow rapid TVT changes, producing\n32: responsive but noisier paths that track local dip). Ensembling these gives the\n33: model both structural trend and local sensitivity. These paths + their ensemble\n34: statistics + GR residuals at various offsets = 24-75 features fed into the same\n35: LightGBM.\n37: For the geophysicists: this is the same algorithm as Hale's dynamic warping of\n38: seismic images. Not conventional seed-based autotracking, but the DP-based\n39: approach that finds optimal shifts to align two signals. The cost functions are\n40: structurally identical:\n42: Dynamic image warping (Hale, 2013) — find shifts u(t) that align image f to\n43: image g:\n46: min sum_i [ (f(t_i) - g(t_i + u_i))^2 + lambda * |u_i - u_{i-1}| ]\n49: Geosteering TVT tracking (this notebook) — find TVT states that align lateral GR\n50: to typewell GR:\n53: min sum_i [ (GR_obs_i - GR_typewell[state_i])^2 / sigma + mu * |state_i -\n54: state_{i-1}| ]\n57: Both minimize a data-fit term (how well the observed signal matches the\n58: reference at the candidate position) plus a regularization term (how much the\n59: shift or state jumps between adjacent positions). Replace \"seismic trace\" with\n60: \"lateral GR log\", \"reference image\" with \"typewell\", \"shift\" with \"TVT state\",\n61: and you have the same algorithm. The same DP structure appears in speech signal\n62: alignment (Sakoe and Chiba, 1978), sequence decoding (Viterbi, 1967), and\n63: seismic image warping (Hale, 2013). All are instances of Bellman's (1962)\n64: dynamic programming principle. Pure numpy, no Numba, deterministic, ~25 min for\n65: 773 wells.\n67: What worked:\n69: • The Viterbi ensemble mean became the #1 feature by LightGBM gain importance,\n70: ahead of all NCC and trajectory features\n71: • 7 of the top 20 features are Viterbi-derived\n72: • OOF improved by 0.46 total (14.806 to 14.346) across two iterations (v1:\n73: +0.154 from 5 Viterbi paths, v2: +0.226 from expanded GR residual families +\n74: confidence features + 2-seed blend)\n76: What didn't work:\n78: • LB barely moved: 14.081 vs 14.082 baseline (a one-thousandth of a foot\n79: improvement)\n80: • This is a textbook CV-overfitting signature: OOF improved 0.46 ft but LB\n81: improved 0.001 ft, while fold variance increased from 0.44 to 0.87. The\n82: Viterbi features fit the training distribution well but don't generalize to\n83: the held-out test wells\n84: • Post-processing (alpha/tau grid-searched on OOF) added only ~0.05\n85: • Confidence features (cost gap between best and second-best Viterbi path)\n86: contributed near-zero gain despite being theoretically the unique advantage\n87: of full-state DP over beam search\n88: • NCC-centered GR residual family was the least informative; anchor-centered\n89: was the most informative\n91: The interesting tension: the model ranks Viterbi features #1 by importance but\n92: the score barely improves on LB. This means the Viterbi paths carry signal that\n93: is partially redundant with existing NCC features. Both measure GR-typewell\n94: similarity; the Viterbi adds sequential consistency but the observation model\n95: (point-by-point GR comparison) is too noisy for the consistency to help much.\n97: The lesson - it's the observation model, not the DP architecture:\n99: The Viterbi architecture is correct: it keeps all states alive (unlike beam\n100: search which prunes to 8-20) and guarantees the global optimum per parameter\n101: set. But its observation cost is crude. A single GR value is a weak\n102: discriminator between adjacent TVT positions. Independent validation from\n103: sleep3r's shuffled-GR experiment: their normal-GR top-10 heatmap coverage was\n104: essentially indistinguishable from shuffled GR (the shuffled version actually\n105: scored marginally higher, which is the noise floor). Point-by-point GR matching\n106: operates in the noise regime.\n108: From reading the published top-scoring notebooks and discussion posts, the\n109: pattern I see is that the leading solutions compensate not with better decoders,\n110: but with a fundamentally different signal source: spatial structural information\n111: from neighboring wells. The ~5 ft gap between ~14 and ~9 RMSE appears to be not\n112: about more features or better inference over the GR-typewell match, but about\n113: adding a second, independent information channel.\n115: Quantifying the problem structure - two numbers that look contradictory but\n116: aren't:\n118: We tested the naive prediction TVT = -Z + C (flat formation assumption). In the\n119: lateral section: 55 ft RMSE. Per-well correlation between dTVT and -dZ\n120: increments: median r = 0.79 (r-squared = 0.62).\n122: These are consistent, not contradictory. The r = 0.79 measures increment\n123: direction correlation: when Z goes down, TVT usually goes up, and vice versa.\n124: But the within-lateral dTVT/dZ slope is ~+0.057, not the -1 that the naive model\n125: assumes. Z wiggles ~14x more than TVT in the lateral because the bit is drilling\n126: roughly horizontal through a nearly flat formation. High directional correlation\n127: + near-zero slope + large cumulative drift coexist: the naive model accumulates\n128: a growing error despite \"predicting the right direction\" 62% of the time. Our GR\n129: matching reduces 55 to 14.3 ft by capturing the actual formation dip; the\n130: remaining gap to sub-10 requires spatial structure from neighboring wells.\n132: A cautionary tale - GR scaling:\n134: The first run produced completely flat paths (path_range = 0.0 for all five\n135: configs). Root cause: clean_gr() z-scores the GR, shrinking values to [-3, 3].\n136: With z-scored GR, the observation cost was ~0.03/position while movement costs\n137: were 4-35. The DP never justified leaving the anchor. Fix: raw GR in API units\n138: for the Viterbi cost function, while NCC features continue using z-scored GR\n139: upstream. If you're building a physics-based cost function on top of normalized\n140: features, check the scaling.\n142: Cross-domain connections:\n144: The same DP structure appears across fields under different names:\n146: • Seismic image warping: Hale (2013) - \"dynamic warping\"; Yan and Wu (2021) -\n147: \"DP-based horizon extraction\"\n148: • Speech recognition: Sakoe and Chiba (1978) - \"dynamic time warping\"\n149: • Communications: Viterbi (1967) - \"Viterbi algorithm\"\n150: • Bioinformatics: gene structure decoding - \"HMM decoding\"\n151: • Automated geosteering: Zeng, Bhaidasna, and Zou (IADC/SPE-230729-MS, 2026) -\n152: particle filter + DTW, validating the log-correlation approach in a\n153: commercial context\n155: The geoscience community knows this as \"dynamic warping\" or \"DP-based horizon\n156: extraction\"; the signal processing community calls it the \"Viterbi algorithm.\"\n157: Four-phase structure is identical: initialize, forward-accumulate, minimize\n158: terminal state, backtrack.\n160: A second algorithmic pattern: structural guide + local matcher\n162: The DP discussion above covers the sequential tracker side of the problem. But\n163: from reviewing the top-scoring public notebooks in this competition\n164: (particularly the v43 spatial-pooling notebook and the inference-stack\n165: notebook), I see a second pattern at work: a smooth regional surface provides a\n166: structural backbone, and local signal matching corrects the residual.\n168: In seismic interpretation, Gogia et al. (2020, Interpretation/SEG-dGB) built a\n169: hybrid horizon tracker that combines inversion-based dip flattening (a smooth\n170: surface fitted to the regional dip field) with similarity-based autotracking\n171: (local event correlation that snaps the surface to the correct reflector).\n172: Without the autotracker, the dip-only surface drifts off-phase; without the dip\n173: surface, the autotracker creates holes and loop-skips. The hybrid outperforms\n174: either component alone.\n176: The same decomposition appears in this competition. The spatial structural\n177: backbone (formation plane fits from neighboring wells, implemented as\n178: FormationPlaneKNN in the top-scoring public notebooks) is the dip-flattening\n179: analog: a smooth regional surface that predicts TVT from spatial position alone.\n180: GR-typewell matching (NCC, Viterbi, particle filters) is the autotracker analog:\n\n### rogii_discussion_703775.md\n1: Discussion 703775 not found in database.\n\n### rogii_discussion_703786.md\n1: Discussion 703786 not found in database.\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
